The structural temperature is opposite to the actual body temperature, e.g. estrogen or fatigue increase the structural temperature and lower the body's temperature. Progesterone decreases the structural temperature and increases the temperature. Like putting ice on a thermostat.

I was thinking how Progesterone lowers the "structural temperature" of tissues (making water more structured like ice and less like the MRI-detectable bulk water in tumors) and how Menthol produces a cooling sensation which is why it's in Tiger Balm, mint lattes, cigarettes, etc.

The normie science explanation for why Menthol feels cool is it triggers some random thermoreceptor, but it made me think if it's a local anesthetic that feels so cooling in drinks, ointments, or smoke, it might have other progestogenic effects. Found this 60s article on Chudmed:

Both Progesterone and Menthol unblock a suppressed Galactose metabolism and increase Galactose's conversion into CO2 in those cases. Progesterone stimulates Galactose metabolism, Galactose is called the brain sugar...
